# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: signed-distance-fields
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] A **distance transform**, also known as **distance map** or **distance field**, is a derived representation of a digital image.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] The choice of the term depends on the point of view on the object in question: whether the initial image is transformed into another representation, or it is simply endowed with an additional map or field.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] Distance fields can also be signed, in the case where it is important to distinguish whether the point is inside or outside of the shape.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] The map labels each pixel of the image with the distance to the nearest *obstacle pixel*.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] A most common type of obstacle pixel is a *boundary pixel* in a binary image.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] See the image for an example of a Chebyshev distance transform on a binary image.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] Usually the transform/map is qualified with the chosen metric.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] For example, one may speak of **Manhattan distance transform**, if the underlying metric is Manhattan distance.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] There are several algorithms to compute the distance transform for these different distance metrics, however the computation of the exact Euclidean distance transform (EEDT) needs special treatment if it is computed on the image grid.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] Applications are digital image processing (e.g., blurring effects, skeletonizing), motion planning in robotics, medical-image analysis for prenatal genetic testing, and even pathfinding.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] Uniformly-sampled signed distance fields have been used for GPU-accelerated font smoothing, for example by Valve researchers.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] Signed distance fields can also be used for (3D) solid modelling.
[src:signed-distance-fields/distance-transform] Rendering on typical GPU hardware requires conversion to polygon meshes, e.g. by the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] An **isosurface** is a three-dimensional analog of an isoline.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] It is a surface that represents points of a constant value (e.g. pressure, temperature, velocity, density) within a volume of space; in other words, it is a level set of a continuous function whose domain is 3-space.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] The term *isoline* is also sometimes used for domains of more than 3 dimensions.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] Isosurfaces are normally displayed using computer graphics, and are used as data visualization methods in computational fluid dynamics (CFD), allowing engineers to study features of a fluid flow (gas or liquid) around objects, such as aircraft wings.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] An isosurface may represent an individual shock wave in supersonic flight, or several isosurfaces may be generated showing a sequence of pressure values in the air flowing around a wing.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] Isosurfaces tend to be a popular form of visualization for volume datasets since they can be rendered by a simple polygonal model, which can be drawn on the screen very quickly.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] In medical imaging, isosurfaces may be used to represent regions of a particular density in a three-dimensional CT scan, allowing the visualization of internal organs, bones, or other structures.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] Numerous other disciplines that are interested in three-dimensional data often use isosurfaces to obtain information about pharmacology, chemistry, geophysics and meteorology.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] The marching cubes algorithm was first published in the 1987 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Lorensen and Cline, and it creates a surface by intersecting the edges of a data volume grid with the volume contour.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] Where the surface intersects the edge the algorithm creates a vertex.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] By using a table of different triangles depending on different patterns of edge intersections the algorithm can create a surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] This algorithm has solutions for implementation both on the CPU and on the GPU.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] The asymptotic decider algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to resolve the possibility of ambiguity in it.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] The marching tetrahedra algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to solve an ambiguity in that algorithm and to create higher quality output surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] The Surface Nets algorithm places an intersecting vertex in the middle of a volume voxel instead of at the edges, leading to a smoother output surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] The dual contouring algorithm was first published in the 2002 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Ju and Losasso, developed as an extension to both surface nets and marching cubes.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] It retains a dual vertex within the voxel but no longer at the center.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] Dual contouring leverages the position and normal of where the surface crosses the edges of a voxel to interpolate the position of the dual vertex within the voxel.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] This has the benefit of retaining sharp or smooth surfaces where surface nets often look blocky or incorrectly beveled.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] Dual contouring often uses surface generation that leverages octrees as an optimization to adapt the number of triangles in output to the complexity of the surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] Examples of isosurfaces are 'Metaballs' or 'blobby objects' used in 3D visualisation.
[src:signed-distance-fields/isosurface] A more general way to construct an isosurface is to use the function representation.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The algorithm was developed by William E.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Cline as a result of their research for General Electric.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] At General Electric they worked on a way to efficiently visualize data from CT and MRI devices.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The premise of the algorithm is to divide the input volume into a discrete set of cubes.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] By assuming linear reconstruction filtering, each cube, which contains a piece of a given isosurface, can easily be identified because the sample values at the cube vertices must span the target isosurface value.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] For each cube containing a section of the isosurface, a triangular mesh that approximates the behavior of the trilinear interpolant in the interior cube is generated.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The first published version of the algorithm exploited rotational and reflective symmetry and also sign changes to build the table with 15 unique cases.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] However, due to the existence of ambiguities in the trilinear interpolant behavior in the cube faces and interior, the meshes extracted by the Marching Cubes presented discontinuities and topological issues.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Given a cube of the grid, a face ambiguity occurs when its face vertices have alternating signs.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] That is, the vertices of one diagonal on this face are positive and the vertices on the other are negative.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Observe that in this case, the signs of the face vertices are insufficient to determine the correct way to triangulate the isosurface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Similarly, an interior ambiguity occurs when the signs of the cube vertices are insufficient to determine the correct surface triangulation, i.e., when multiple triangulations are possible for the same cube configuration.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The popularity of the Marching Cubes and its widespread adoption resulted in several improvements in the algorithm to deal with the ambiguities and to correctly track the behavior of the interpolant.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Durst in 1988 was the first to note that the triangulation table proposed by Lorensen and Cline was incomplete, and that certain Marching Cubes cases allow multiple triangulations.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Durst's 'additional reference' was to an earlier, more efficient (see de Araujo) isosurface polygonization algorithm by Wyvill, Wyvill and McPheeters.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Later, Nielson and Hamann in 1991 observed the existence of ambiguities in the interpolant behavior on the face of the cube.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] They proposed a test called Asymptotic Decider to correctly track the interpolant on the faces of the cube.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] In fact, as observed by Natarajan in 1994, this ambiguity problem also occurs inside the cube.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] In his work, the author proposed a disambiguation test based on the interpolant critical points, and added four new cases to the Marching Cubes triangulation table (subcases of the cases 3, 4, 6 and 7).
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] At this point, even with all the improvements proposed to the algorithm and its triangulation table, the meshes generated by the Marching Cubes still had topological incoherencies.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The Marching Cubes 33, proposed by Chernyaev in 1995, is one of the first isosurface extraction algorithms intended to preserve the topology of the trilinear interpolant.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] In his work, Chernyaev extends to 33 the number of cases in the triangulation lookup table.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] He then proposes a different approach to solve the interior ambiguities, which is based on the Asymptotic Decider.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Later, in 2003, Nielson proved that Chernyaev's lookup table is complete and can represent all the possible behaviors of the trilinear interpolant, and Lewiner et al. proposed an implementation to the algorithm.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Also in 2003 Lopes and Brodlie extended the tests proposed by Natarajan.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] In 2013, Custodio et al. noted and corrected algorithmic inaccuracies that compromised the topological correctness of the mesh generated by the Marching Cubes 33 algorithm proposed by Chernyaev.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The algorithm proceeds through the scalar field, taking eight neighbor locations at a time (thus forming an imaginary cube), then determining the polygon(s) needed to represent the part of the isosurface that passes through this cube.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The individual polygons are then fused into the desired surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] This is done by creating an index to a precalculated array of 256 possible polygon configurations (28=256) within the cube, by treating each of the 8 scalar values as a bit in an 8-bit integer.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] If the scalar's value is higher than the iso-value (i.e., it is inside the surface) then the appropriate bit is set to one, while if it is lower (outside), it is set to zero.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The final value, after all eight scalars are checked, is the actual index to the polygon indices array.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Finally each vertex of the generated polygons is placed on the appropriate position along the cube's edge by linearly interpolating the two scalar values that are connected by that edge.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The gradient of the scalar field at each grid point is also the normal vector of a hypothetical isosurface passing from that point.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Therefore, these normals may be interpolated along the edges of each cube to find the normals of the generated vertices which are essential for shading the resulting mesh with some illumination model.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] An implementation of the marching cubes algorithm was patented as United States Patent 4,710,876.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] Another similar algorithm was developed, called marching tetrahedra, in order to circumvent the patent as well as solve a minor ambiguity problem of marching cubes with some cube configurations.
[src:signed-distance-fields/marching-cubes] The patent expired in 2005, and it is now legal for the graphics community to use it without royalties since more than the 20 years have passed from its issue date (December 1, 1987).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The term "Ray Casting" was introduced by Scott Roth while at the General Motors Research Labs from 1978–1980.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] His paper, "Ray Casting for Modeling Solids", describes modeled solid objects by combining primitive solids, such as blocks and cylinders, using the set operators union (+), intersection (&), and difference (−).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The general idea of using these binary operators for solid modeling is largely due to Voelcker and Requicha's geometric modelling group at the University of Rochester.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Before ray casting (and ray tracing), computer graphics algorithms projected surfaces or edges (e.g., lines) from the 3D world to the image plane where visibility logic had to be applied.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The world-to-image plane projection is a 3D homogeneous coordinate system transformation, also known as 3D projection, affine transformation, or projective transform (homography).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Rendering an image this way is difficult to achieve with hidden surface/edge removal.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Plus, silhouettes of curved surfaces have to be explicitly solved for whereas it is an implicit by-product of ray casting, so there is no need to explicitly solve for it whenever the view changes.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Ray casting greatly simplified image rendering of 3D objects and scenes because a line transforms to a line.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] So, instead of projecting curved edges and surfaces in the 3D scene to the 2D image plane, transformed lines (rays) are intersected with the objects in the scene.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] A homogeneous coordinate transformation is represented by a 4×4 matrix.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The mathematical technique is common to computer graphics and geometric modeling.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] A transform includes rotations around the three axes, independent scaling along the axes, translations in 3D, and even skewing.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Transforms are easily concatenated via matrix arithmetic.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For use with a 4×4 matrix, a point is represented by [*X*, *Y*, *Z*, 1], and a direction vector is represented by [*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*, 0].
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Ray casting is the most basic of many computer graphics rendering algorithms that use the geometric algorithm of ray tracing.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Ray tracing-based rendering algorithms operate in image order to render three-dimensional scenes to two-dimensional images.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Geometric rays are traced from the eye of the observer to sample the light (radiance) travelling toward the observer from the ray direction.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The speed and simplicity of ray casting comes from computing the color of the light without recursively tracing additional rays that sample the radiance incident on the point that the ray hit.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This eliminates the possibility of accurately rendering reflections, refractions, or the natural falloff of shadows; however all of these elements can be faked to a degree, by creative use of texture maps or other methods.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The high speed of calculation made ray casting a handy rendering method in early real-time 3D video games.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The idea behind ray casting is to trace rays from the eye, one per pixel, and find the closest object blocking the path of that ray—think of an image as a screen-door, with each square in the screen being a pixel.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This is then the object the eye sees through that pixel.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Using the material properties and the effect of the lights in the scene, this algorithm can determine the shading of this object.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The simplifying assumption is made that if a surface faces a light, the light will reach that surface and not be blocked or in shadow.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The shading of the surface is computed using traditional 3D computer graphics shading models.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] One important advantage ray casting offered over older scanline algorithms was its ability to easily deal with non-planar surfaces and solids, such as cones and spheres.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] If a mathematical surface can be intersected by a ray, it can be rendered using ray casting.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Elaborate objects can be created by using solid modelling techniques and easily rendered.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Light rays and the camera geometry form the basis for all geometric reasoning here.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This figure shows a pinhole camera model for perspective effect in image processing and a parallel camera model for mass analysis.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The simple pinhole camera model consists of a focal point (or eye point) and a square pixel array (or screen).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Straight light rays pass through the pixel array to connect the focal point with the scene, one ray per pixel.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] To shade pictures, the rays’ intensities are measured and stored as pixels.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The reflecting surface responsible for a pixel’s value intersects the pixel’s ray.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] When the focal length, distance between focal point and screen, is infinite, then the view is called “parallel” because all light rays are parallel to each other, perpendicular to the screen.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Although the perspective view is natural for making pictures, some applications need rays that can be uniformly distributed in space.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For modeling convenience, a typical standard coordinate system for the camera has the screen in the X–Y plane, the scene in the +Z half space, and the focal point on the −Z axis.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] A *ray* is simply a straight line in the 3D space of the camera model.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] It is best defined in parameterized form as a point vector (*X*0, *Y*0, *Z*0) and a direction vector (*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] In this form, points on the line are ordered and accessed via a single parameter t.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] If the vector is normalized, then the parameter t is distance along the line.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Where n is the number of ray-surface intersections.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The ordered list of ray parameters, *t* [*i*], denote the enter–exit points.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The ray enters a solid at point *t* [1], exits at *t* [2], enters a solid at *t* [3], etc.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Point *t* [1] is closest to the camera and *t* [*n*] is furthest.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] In association with the ray parameters, the surface pointers contain a unique address for the intersected surface’s information.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The surface can have various properties such as color, specularity, transparency with/without refraction, translucency, etc.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The solid associated with the surface may have its own physical properties such as density.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This could be useful, for instance, when an object consists of an assembly of different materials and the overall center of mass and moments of inertia are of interest.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Three algorithms using ray casting are to make line drawings, to make shaded pictures, and to compute volumes and other physical properties.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Each algorithm, given a camera model, casts one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For computing volume, the resolution of the pixel screen to use depends on the desired accuracy of the solution.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For line drawings and picture shading, the resolution determines the quality of the image.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] To draw the visible edges of a solid, generate one ray per pixel moving top-down, left-right in the screen.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Evaluate each ray in order to identify the visible surface *S* [1], the first surface pointer in the sorted list of ray-surface intersections.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] If the visible surface at pixel location (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* − 1, *Y* ), then display a vertical line one pixel long centered at (*X* − ½, *Y* ).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Similarly, if the visible surface at (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* − 1), then display a horizontal line one pixel long centered at (*X*, *Y* − ½).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The resulting drawing will consist of horizontal and vertical edges only, looking jagged in coarse resolutions.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Roth’s ray casting system generated the images of solid objects on the right.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Box enclosures, dynamic bounding, and coherence were used for optimization.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For each picture, the screen was sampled with a density of about 100×100 (i.e., 10,000) rays and new edges were located via binary searches.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Then all edges were followed by casting additional rays at one pixel increments on the two sides of the edges.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Each picture was drawn on a Tektronix tube at 780×780 resolution.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] To make a shaded picture, again cast one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This time, however, use the visible surface pointer S[1] at each pixel to access the description of the surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] From this, compute the surface normal at the visible point *t* [1].
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The pixel’s value, the displayable light intensity, is proportional to the cosine of the angle formed by the surface normal and the light-source-to-surface vector.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Processing all pixels this way produces a raster-type picture of the scene.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The volume (and similar properties) of a solid bounded by curved surfaces is easily computed by the “approximating sums” integration method, by approximating the solid with a set of rectangular parallelepipeds.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This is accomplished by taking an “in-depth” picture of the solid in a parallel view.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Casting rays through the screen into the solid partitions the solid into volume elements.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Two dimensions of the parallelepipeds are constant, defined by the 2D spacing of rays in the screen.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The third dimension is variable, defined by the enter–exit point computed.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] where L is defined as the length of the direction vector.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Each ${\tfrac {t[i]\ -\ t[i-1]}{L}}$ is a length of a ray segment that is inside of the solid.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This figure shows the parallelepipeds for a modeled solid using ray casting.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This is a use of parallel-projection camera model.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This figure shows an example of the binary operators in a composition tree using “+” and “−” where a single ray is evaluated.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The ray casting procedure starts at the top of the solid composition tree, recursively descends to the bottom, classifies the ray with respect to the primitive solids, and then returns up the tree combining the classifications of the left and right subtrees.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This figure illustrates the combining of the left and right classifications for all three binary operators.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Ray casting is a natural modeling tool for making shaded pictures.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The grayscale ray-casting system developed by Scott Roth and Daniel Bass at GM Research Labs produced pictures on a Ramtek color raster display around 1979.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This figure shows a table scene with shadows from two point light sources.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Shading algorithms that implement all of the realistic effects are computationally expensive, but relatively simple.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For example, the following figure shows the additional rays that could be cast for a single light source.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For a single pixel in the image to be rendered, the algorithm casts a ray starting at the focal point and determines that it intersects a semi-transparent rectangle and a shiny circle.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] An additional ray must then be cast starting at that point in the direction symmetrically opposite the surface normal at the ray-surface intersection point in order to determine what is visible in the mirrored reflection.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] That ray intersects the triangle which is opaque.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Finally, each ray-surface intersection point is tested to determine if it is in shadow.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The “Shadow feeler” ray is cast from the ray-surface intersection point to the light source to determine if any other surface blocks that pathway.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The secondary ray is then processed as a specular ray.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For the refraction formula and pictorial examples, see Whitted’s paper.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Ray casting qualifies as a brute force method for solving problems.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The minimal algorithm is simple, particularly in consideration of its many applications and ease of use, but applications typically cast many rays.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Millions of rays may be cast to render a single frame of an animated film.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Computer processing time increases with the resolution of the screen and the number of primitive solids/surfaces in the composition.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] By using minimum bounding boxes around the solids in the composition tree, the exhaustive search for a ray-solid intersection resembles an efficient binary search.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The brute force algorithm does an exhaustive search because it always visits all the nodes in the tree—transforming the ray into primitives’ local coordinate systems, testing for ray-surface intersections, and combining the classifications—even when the ray clearly misses the solid.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] In order to detect a “clear miss”, a faster algorithm uses the binary composition tree as a hierarchical representation of the space that the solid composition occupies.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] But all position, shape, and size information is stored at the leaves of the tree where primitive solids reside.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The top and intermediate nodes in the tree only specify combine operators.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Characterizing with enclosures the space that all solids fill gives all nodes in the tree an abstract summary of position and size information.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Then, the quick “ray intersects enclosure” tests guide the search in the hierarchy.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] When the test fails at an intermediate node in the tree, the ray is guaranteed to classify as out of the composite, so recursing down its subtrees to further investigate is unnecessary.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Accurately assessing the cost savings for using enclosures is difficult because it depends on the spatial distribution of the primitives (the complexity distribution) and on the organization of the composition tree.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The following are miscellaneous performance improvements made in Roth’s paper on ray casting, but there have been considerable improvements subsequently made by others.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] If the operator at a composite node in the tree is − or & and the ray classifies as out of the composite’s left sub-solid, then the ray will classify as out of the composite regardless of the ray’s classification with respect to the right sub-solid.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] So, classifying the ray with respect to the right sub-solid is unnecessary and should be avoided for efficiency.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] By initially combining the screen-to-scene transform with the primitive’s scene-to-local transform and storing the resulting screen-to-local transforms in the primitive’s data structures, one ray transform per ray-surface intersection is eliminated.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Given a deep composition tree, recursion can be expensive in combination with allocating and freeing up memory.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Recursion can be simulated using static arrays as stacks.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] If only the visible edges of the solid are to be displayed, the ray casting algorithm can dynamically bound the ray to cut off the search.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] That is, after finding that a ray intersects a sub-solid, the algorithm can use the intersection point closest to the screen to tighten the depth bound for the “ray intersections box” test.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This only works for the + part of the tree, starting at the top.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] With – and &, nearby “in” parts of the ray may later become “out”.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The principle of coherence is that the surfaces visible at two neighboring pixels are more likely to be the same than different.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Developers of computer graphics and vision systems have applied this empirical truth for efficiency and performance.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For line drawings, the image area containing edges is normally much less than the total image area, so ray casting should be concentrated around the edges and not in the open regions.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This can be effectively implemented by sparsely sampling the screen with rays and then locating, when neighboring rays identify different visible surfaces, the edges via binary searches.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The jagged edges caused by aliasing is an undesirable effect of point sampling techniques and is a classic problem with raster display algorithms.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Linear or smoothly curved edges will appear jagged and are particularly objectionable in animations because movement of the image makes the edges appear fuzzy or look like little moving escalators.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Also, details in the scene smaller than the spacing between rays may be lost.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The jagged edges in a line drawing can be smoothed by edge following.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The purpose of such an algorithm is to minimize the number of lines needed to draw the picture within one pixel accuracy.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The line drawings above were drawn this way.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] To smooth the jagged edges in a shaded picture with subpixel accuracy, additional rays should be cast for information about the edges.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] (See Supersampling for a general approach.) Edges are formed by the intersection of surfaces or by the profile of a curved surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Applying "Coherence" as described above via binary search, if the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* + 1, *Y* ), then a ray could be generated midway between them at (*X* + ½, *Y* ) and the visible surface there identified.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The distance between sample points could be further subdivided, but the search need not be deep.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The primary search depth to smooth jagged edges is a function of the intensity gradient across the edge.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] For the history of ray casting, see Ray tracing (graphics) as both are essentially the same technique under different names.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Scott Roth had invented the term "ray casting" before having heard of "ray tracing".
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Additionally, Scott Roth's development of ray casting at GM Research Labs occurred concurrently with Turner Whitted's ray tracing work at Bell Labs.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] In early first person games, raycasting was used to efficiently render a 3D world from a 2D playing field using a simple one-dimensional scan over the horizontal width of the screen.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Early first-person shooters used 2D ray casting as a technique to create a 3D effect from a 2D world.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] While the world appears 3D, the player cannot look up or down or only in limited angles with shearing distortion.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This style of rendering eliminates the need to fire a ray for each pixel in the frame as is the case with modern engines; once the hit point is found the projection distortion is applied to the surface texture and an entire vertical column is copied from the result into the frame.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] This style of rendering also imposes limitations on the type of rendering which can be performed, for example **depth sorting** but depth buffering may not.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] That is polygons must be full in front of or behind one another, they may not partially overlap or intersect.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The video game *Wolfenstein 3D* was built from a square based grid of uniform height walls meeting solid-colored floors and ceilings.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] In order to draw the world, a single ray was traced for every column of screen pixels and a vertical slice of wall texture was selected and scaled according to where in the world the ray hits a wall and how far it travels before doing so.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The purpose of the grid based levels was twofold — ray-wall collisions can be found more quickly since the potential hits become more predictable and memory overhead is reduced.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] However, encoding wide-open areas takes extra space.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The Raven Software game *ShadowCaster* uses an improved Wolfenstein-based engine with added floors and ceilings texturing and variable wall heights.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The Voxel Space engine developed by NovaLogic for the *Comanche* games traced a ray through each column of screen pixels and tested each ray against points in a heightmap.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Then it transformed each element of the heightmap into a column of pixels, determined which are visible (that is, have not been occluded by pixels that have been drawn in front), and drew them with the corresponding color from the texture map.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] Later DOS games like *id Software's DOOM* kept many of the raycasting 2.5D restrictions for speed but went on to switch to alternative rendering techniques (like BSP), making them no longer raycasting engines.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] The problem has been investigated for various settings: space dimension, types of objects, restrictions on query rays, etc.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-casting] One technique is to use a sparse voxel octree.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] The technique dates back to at least the 1980s; the 1989 paper "Hypertexture" by Ken Perlin contains an early example of a ray marching method.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] In **sphere tracing**, or **sphere-assisted ray marching** an intersection point is approximated between the ray and a surface defined by a signed distance function (SDF).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] The SDF is evaluated for each iteration in order to be able take as large steps as possible without missing any part of the surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] A threshold is used to cancel further iteration when a point has reached that is close enough to the surface.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] As powerful GPU hardware became more widely available, this method was popularized by the demoscene and Inigo Quilez, co-creator of Shadertoy.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] For simple scenes with basic 3D shapes, ray marching does not have many benefits over ray tracing (which finds intersections without marching through the space).
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] Strengths of SDF ray marching are, for example, when morphing shapes, approximating soft shadows, repetition of geometry, and algorithmically defined scenes.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] Signed distance functions exist for many primitive 3D shapes.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] They can be combined using mathematical operations like modulo and booleans to form more complex surfaces.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] For instance, taking the modulus of an SDF's input coordinates tiles its volume across all of space, and taking the maximum of two SDFs gives their volumes' surface of intersection.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] Because SDFs can be defined for many fractals, sphere tracing is often used for 3D fractal rendering.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] A similar technique to sphere-assisted ray marching, the use of cubes and taxicab distance can be used to render voxel volumes.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] In volumetric ray marching, each ray is traced so that color and/or density can be sampled along the ray and then be combined into a final pixel color.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] This is often used for example when rendering clouds or 3D medical scans.
[src:signed-distance-fields/ray-marching] When rendering screen space effects, such as screen space reflection (SSR) and screen space shadows, rays are traced using G-buffers, where depth and surface normal data is stored per each 2D pixel.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] The function has positive values at points *x* inside Ω, it decreases in value as *x* approaches the boundary of Ω where the signed distance function is zero, and it takes negative values outside of Ω.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] However, the alternative convention is also sometimes taken instead (i.e., negative inside Ω and positive outside).
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] The concept also sometimes goes by the name **oriented distance function/field**.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] Let Ω be a subset of a metric space *X* with metric *d*, and $\partial \Omega$ be its boundary.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] If the boundary of Ω is *C**k* for *k* ≥ 2 (see Differentiability classes) then *d* is *C**k* on points sufficiently close to the boundary of Ω.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] where *N* is the inward normal vector field.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] The signed distance function is thus a differentiable extension of the normal vector field.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] In particular, the Hessian of the signed distance function on the boundary of Ω gives the Weingarten map.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] If, further, Γ is a region sufficiently close to the boundary of Ω that *f* is twice continuously differentiable on it, then there is an explicit formula involving the Weingarten map *W**x* for the Jacobian of changing variables in terms of the signed distance function and nearest boundary point.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] where det denotes the determinant and *dS**u* indicates that we are taking the surface integral.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] Algorithms for calculating the signed distance function include the efficient fast marching method, fast sweeping method and the more general level-set method.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] For voxel rendering, a fast algorithm for calculating the SDF in taxicab geometry uses summed-area tables.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] Signed distance functions are applied, for example, in real-time rendering, for instance the method of SDF ray marching, and computer vision.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] SDF has been used to describe object geometry in real-time rendering, usually in a raymarching context, starting in the mid 2000s.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] By 2007, Valve was using SDFs to render large pixel-size (or high DPI) smooth fonts with GPU acceleration in its games.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] Valve's method is not perfect as it runs in raster space in order to avoid the computational complexity of solving the problem in the (continuous) vector space.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] The rendered text often loses sharp corners.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] In 2014, an improved method was presented by Behdad Esfahbod.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] Behdad's GLyphy approximates the font's Bézier curves with arc splines, accelerated by grid-based discretization techniques (which culls too-far-away points) to run in real time.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] A modified version of SDF was introduced as a loss function to minimise the error in interpenetration of pixels while rendering multiple objects.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] In particular, for any pixel that does not belong to an object, if it lies outside the object in rendition, no penalty is imposed; if it does, a positive value proportional to its distance inside the object is imposed.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] In 2020, the FOSS game engine Godot 4.0 received SDF-based real-time global illumination (SDFGI), that became a compromise between more realistic voxel-based GI and baked GI.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] Its core advantage is that it can be applied to infinite space, which allows developers to use it for open-world games.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] In 2023, the authors of the Zed text editor announced a GPUI framework that draws all UI elements using the GPU at 120 fps.
[src:signed-distance-fields/signed-distance-function] The work makes use of Inigo Quilez's list of geometric primitives in SDF, Figma co-founder Evan Wallace's Gaussian blur in SDF, and a new rounded rectangle SDF.
